{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525860"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:18:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:18:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14099"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14099"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.65,0.12,0.13,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6769"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109705"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6769"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14099"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92102"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"176"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1845"},{"type":"tags","id":"2196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2316"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11140"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14847"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44307"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109705"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of fatigue, back pain, and recurrent chest infections. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears pale. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Blood tests reveal a haemoglobin of 98 g/L (115-165) and creatinine of 130 \u00b5mol/L (45-90). Urinalysis shows 2+ protein. Further urine testing reveals a protein-creatinine ratio (PCR) of 350 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;15) and an albumin-creatinine ratio (ACR) of 50 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;3).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lymph node biopsy","Serum protein electrophoresis","Double-stranded DNA antibody test","Renal tract ultrasound","24-hour urine collection"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and laboratory findings suggestive of multiple myeloma. The most appropriate next investigation is \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum protein electrophoresis\u003C/strong\u003E, which can detect the presence of monoclonal proteins (M-proteins) characteristic of myeloma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture is consistent with myeloma: fatigue (likely due to anaemia), back pain (possibly from bone involvement), recurrent infections (due to immunodeficiency), anaemia, renal impairment, and proteinuria. Notably, there is a disproportionately high protein-creatinine ratio (PCR) compared to the albumin-creatinine ratio (ACR). This discrepancy suggests the presence of non-albumin proteins in the urine, which in myeloma are typically monoclonal light chains (Bence Jones proteins).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elymph node biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as the first investigation for suspected myeloma. Lymphadenopathy is not a typical feature of myeloma, and the diagnosis is usually made through blood and urine tests, followed by bone marrow biopsy if indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Edouble-stranded DNA antibody test\u003C/strong\u003E is useful in the diagnosis of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). While SLE can cause proteinuria, it does not typically present with the constellation of symptoms seen in this patient and usually presents with proteinuria that is predominantly albuminuria (i.e. glomerular in origin).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal tract ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered later in the workup, particularly if there is concern about obstructive uropathy. However, it is not the most appropriate next step given the high suspicion for myeloma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urine collection\u003C/strong\u003E can provide accurate quantification of proteinuria, but it is does not add diagnostic clarity. The spot urine PCR and ACR already provide valuable information about the nature of the proteinuria, suggesting the presence of non-albumin proteins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf serum protein electrophoresis is positive for a monoclonal protein, further investigations would include serum free light chain assay, bone marrow biopsy, and skeletal survey or low-dose CT to evaluate for lytic bone lesions. These tests, along with the clinical presentation, would help confirm the diagnosis of multiple myeloma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Myeloma can cause proteinuria with a disproportionately high protein-creatinine ratio (PCR) compared to albumin-creatinine ratio (ACR) due to the presence of monoclonal light chains."],"references":["CARROLL MF, TEMTE JL. Proteinuria in Adults: A Diagnostic Approach. American Family Physician [Internet]. 2000 Sep 15;62(6):1333\u201340. Available from: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2000/0915/p1333.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92102"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14099"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92102"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-25T03:12:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-25T03:12:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6769"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109705"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72"